In an era where many are craving more Independent Films, I was thinking about our 2014 release of @bellavitafilm 🇮🇹 hard to believe it was 10 years ago I was riding my bike every day to venice beach to sit in on edit sessions with Carl Cramer and Ting Poo.  Part travelogue, part surf-adventure, all Italian, Bella Vita was about as independent as it gets, with a tiny crew shooting 35mm Film and all our Italian friends grabbing cases  and lugging gear to the beach.  If you haven’t seen it for a while, give it another look.  @chrisdelmoro111 and the Italian surf community offer an inspiring way to live life.  Available on our website bellavitafilm.com or via most VOD rental platforms #itunes #amazon #youtube

Final picture.  Layback sound.  QC again.  Hard to believe it was 10 years ago this week that the final master and export of @bellavitafilm dropped into my hand.  It began as a Bintang fueled idea.  Two plane tickets.  Cases of gear. A stack of boards and a crew of locals waiting for us with open arms.  @chrisdelmoro111 and I jumped deep into Italian surf culture, a path cleared by Greg, Scott and Anh-Thu.  Scotty K, JT and G. Maoi loading 35mm gear in Rome.  @piergiorgio_castellani waiting by the vines with a warm heart, hosting stars like Rasta, Lauren, Conner, Parker and Leo F.  An outlier in the action-surf-media world, this #indiefilm won more festival awards than anything I’ve ever been a part of.  I am so thankful for everyone’s hard work who helped bring our vision to life.  If you love Italy, a good travelogue or need a dash of inspiration, add “Bella Vita” to your next movie night.  Goes great with close friends, good Italian food and a bit o’ wine if ya like. 

Available on #itunes and bellavitafilm.com

NFL team visit, Chargers vs. Seahawks circa 1982 thanks to Defensive legend (Hall of Famer), then #NBC sportscaster and Nate’s dad, Merlin Olsen.  Kellen Winslow, Steve Largent, all highlights.  Football was my life as a kid and having one of the Ram’s Fearsome Foursome as your buddy’s dad was pretty dang cool. He’d get us into the booth for Raider games.  Dick Enberg was a true gentleman. I learned so much about TV sports.  I have often said that Steve Sabol’s NFL films deserve a lot of credit towards inspiring how I like to shoot.  Happy NFL season opening weekend.  Let the fun begin. ⚡️

2001 OP Pro Boat Trip Challenge.  Part 1. 

May of ‘01 I was gifted the task of producing the TV coverage of a new take on Surfer Mag’s OP Pro.  Curated by Sam George and Paul Taublieub we deployed a flotilla to the Mentawais with an All Star crew of surfers and Media.  Green and star struck by the likes of Andy and @bruceirons  @shanedorian @markocchilupo @_timcurran @cjhobgood_  @kealakennelly Serena @rochelleballard @laynecbeachley not to mention Bernie Baker and @jeffdivinephotographer 🔥 I leaned heavily on support from my buddy Herbie and rock star @mikeprickett_ (@saltnairstudios). Yes, I was the only guy with a 9’0” singlefin.  Which I think Jeff has a photo of me paddling half of back to the boat after a bank vaults cleanup set.  Ugh.  This open was cut by my now longtime editor Carl Cramer.  We shot lotsa film. 16mm and Super 8mm.  Color work and creative direction by @mark_jeremias |  these early shoots for Bluetorch TV really got my imagination running on making my own films. A big thanks to CJ. / Mark / Merrit / Our beloved Scott Paridon / for all the support. 

Mid trip we fell onto an all time day at a little known spot the boat driver called No Kandui 😉 that post coming next …

#surfing #filmmaking #16mm #super8mm #shotonfilm #shotonkodak #indonesia #surfindo #surfermagazine #andyirons #opro

2001 OP Pro.  Part 2.  No Kandui.  As Andy Irons said, “hey, thank you for bringing me”.

Kandui lefts was not well known. I don’t think anyone in our crew had surfed it. So to see everyone charge for the first time made for a magical day.  I remember screaming at Prickett from my boat, “get the 16mm film, shoot everything!” 🎥  I hope you enjoy this little remix.  Andy. Bruce. Shane. Timmy. CJ and Occy livin’ the dream.

I thought my favorite Reyn Spooner happy hour shirt would buy me street cred but producer Dave Brookwell stole the show with his stories of being a caddie as a kid. The OG Becker Surf tee equally gangster. Bill, thanks again for the tour of town in your convertible. Glad I lived through it, so I can self indulgently gain dopamine via social media, posting the same wonderful photo again and again and again... #thebillmurraystories #loopersmovie #golfcaddie #golfcaddies #filmmaker #filmmakerlife #billmurray #voiceover #billmurrayquotes #setlife

Haggerty's Cove. Bob Hogan (L) and Greg Noll (R). I believe a Doc Ball image but apologies as I'm not sure. That Hogan style is off-the-hook. And who was this Haggerty, and what was his relationship to the picturesque church above the beach?

“Haggerty” actually was J.J. Haggarty, a prominent figure in the mercantile trade in Los Angeles in the first part of the 20th century. (The “e” misspelling seems more common than the correct “a” spelling.). 

Haggarty decided to build a summer home after hearing about the new housing being built on the Palos Verdes Peninsula. In 1927, he bought 1½ acres of land on the coast just west of the Malaga Cove area of what would become Palos Verdes Estates. 

The house was completed in 1928 at an estimated cost of a then-astronomical $750,000. Ironically, Haggarty and his wife never spent much time there, as Bertha preferred to live at the Adams District estate known as "Haggarty's Castle".

Then, shortly after the beach house was completed, Haggarty’s business took a huge hit from the Great Depression. His financial misfortunes led to the sale of the house in the early 1930s. Haggarty died on Feb. 9, 1935, and the Palos Verdes Estates house was sold to the London Exploration Co.

It stood vacant for several years, and area residents heard rumors that it was haunted. There were several owners over the next few years, most notably Harry Wheeler, who bought the house after World War II. He collected nude art, and filled the house and grounds with paintings and statues of nude figures.

After Wheeler died in 1949, the house went back on the market for $250,000, but had no takers for several months.

It attracted the attention of the members of a church long in search of a permanent home and that as they say, is history. *details via The Daily Breeze contributor, Sam Gnerre

…As the wind laid down, a calm confidence washed across the crew.  The smell of oil and diesel pungent on the nose, a reminder of how far they’d come.  But water continued to flood in, a brine ridden surge, relentless and cold.  The damn antique clock in the ship’s cabin racing with nowhere to go.  The second hand chewing up any hope, each nudge landing closer to a total loss.  The intrepid Captain sat alone on their precious cargo, quietly cleaning grease from his cracked hands.  A silhouette awash within a blood orange sky, a sight as heroic as it was tragic.  The question was simple.  Should they trust him any longer? 
…
